''See also:'' [[Veronica]].
==English==
===Etymology===
Named from [[w:Saint Veronica|St. Veronica]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /və'rɒnɪkə/

===Noun===
{{en-noun|veronica|veronicas}}
# the [[image]] of Jesus's [[face]] believed to have been made on the cloth with which St Veronica wiped his face as he went to be crucified; or the [[cloth]] used for this
#:*'''1973''': A veil that had wiped off the sweat of Christ?  Who could possibly believe that?  (…)  The only true '''Veronica''' of this century was the ''veronica'' of the matador – the classic slow swing of the cape before the bull’s face, imitating that holy wiping, mocking it. — Nicholas Monsarrat, ''The Kapillan of Malta''
# a devotional image of [[Jesus]]'s face
#:*'''1988''': He wiped the lady’s martini glass, having had some trouble with a kind of '''veronica''' of lipstick, spat in it viciously, then washed it again. — Anthony Burgess, ''Any Old Iron''
# (''Bullfighting'') a circular swinging movement of the [[cape]]
#:*'''1973''': The cougher makes a lunge.  Slothrop sweeps aside, gives him a quick '''veronica''' with his cape, sticks his foot out and trips the kid, who lies on the ground cursing — Thomas Pynchon, ''Gravity's Rainbow''